hook.real_world_problem:
Flipkart's product catalog: a Product belongs to multiple Categories (Electronics, Mobiles, 5G Phones). A Category contains thousands of Products. Standard JPA without the right relationship config:

```java
// WRONG: causes data corruption
@ManyToMany(cascade = CascadeType.ALL)  // ← NEVER cascade ALL on @ManyToMany!
private Set<Category> categories;

// What happens:
product.getCategories().clear();  // removes ALL categories from the product
// CascadeType.ALL includes CascadeType.REMOVE
// → deletes ALL Category entities from the database!
// → 'Electronics' category GONE from all products!

// WRONG: orphanRemoval on @ManyToMany
@OneToMany(orphanRemoval = true)
private List<OrderItem> items;
// Removing an item from the list deletes it from DB
// But if two orders reference the same item... both try to delete it!
```

**The correct patterns:**
```java
// @ManyToMany: NEVER cascade REMOVE or use orphanRemoval
@ManyToMany(cascade = {CascadeType.PERSIST, CascadeType.MERGE})
@JoinTable(
    name = "product_categories",
    joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "product_id"),
    inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "category_id")
)
private Set<Category> categories;

// @OneToMany with orphanRemoval: SAFE because items are owned by ONE order
@OneToMany(cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)
@JoinColumn(name = "order_id")
private List<OrderItem> items;
// orphanRemoval = true: removing item from list → deletes from DB (safe: one owner)
```

Understanding cascade types and ownership is what separates 'JPA works by luck' from 'JPA works correctly'.

concept_explanation.many_to_many:
**@ManyToMany — bidirectional with @JoinTable:**

```java
// Product.java (owning side):
@Entity
public class Product {
    @Id String id;
    String name;

    @ManyToMany(cascade = {CascadeType.PERSIST, CascadeType.MERGE})
    @JoinTable(
        name = "product_categories",             // join table name
        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "product_id"),         // FK to this entity
        inverseJoinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "category_id")  // FK to other entity
    )
    private Set<Category> categories = new HashSet<>();

    // Helper methods to maintain bidirectional relationship:
    public void addCategory(Category cat) {
        categories.add(cat);
        cat.getProducts().add(this);    // ← always update both sides!
    }
    public void removeCategory(Category cat) {
        categories.remove(cat);
        cat.getProducts().remove(this); // ← always update both sides!
    }
}

// Category.java (non-owning / mapped-by side):
@Entity
public class Category {
    @Id String id;
    String name;

    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = "categories")  // ← 'categories' field on Product
    private Set<Product> products = new HashSet<>();

    public Set<Product> getProducts() { return products; }
}

// Usage:
Product phone = new Product("iPhone 15", 89999);
Category electronics = new Category("Electronics");
Category mobiles = new Category("Mobiles");

phone.addCategory(electronics);  // helper method updates both sides
phone.addCategory(mobiles);
productRepo.save(phone);  // saves phone + categories (cascade PERSIST)
// DB: product_categories table has 2 rows
```

concept_explanation.cascade_types:
**Cascade types — what propagates to children:**

```java
// CascadeType enum values:
CascadeType.PERSIST  // save parent → save new children too
CascadeType.MERGE    // update parent → update children too
CascadeType.REMOVE   // delete parent → delete children
CascadeType.REFRESH  // refresh parent → refresh children
CascadeType.DETACH   // detach parent → detach children
CascadeType.ALL      // all of the above

// SAFE patterns:

// @OneToMany (parent owns children exclusively):
@OneToMany(cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)
// ALL is safe: order owns its items exclusively; deleting order deletes items

// @ManyToOne (child reference, don't cascade):
@ManyToOne  // no cascade: saving an Order shouldn't modify/delete its User!

// @ManyToMany (shared references):
@ManyToMany(cascade = {CascadeType.PERSIST, CascadeType.MERGE})
// NEVER REMOVE: categories are shared; deleting product shouldn't delete Electronics!
// NEVER orphanRemoval on @ManyToMany

// DANGEROUS anti-patterns:
@ManyToMany(cascade = CascadeType.ALL)  // WRONG: deletes shared entities!
@ManyToMany(orphanRemoval = true)       // WRONG: doesn't compile (JPA error)

// orphanRemoval:
@OneToMany(orphanRemoval = true)
// When an item is removed from the collection, DELETE it from DB.
// Safe for: exclusive ownership (Order → OrderItem)
// UNSAFE for: shared references (Product → Category)
```

concept_explanation.embeddable:
**@Embeddable — value objects with no identity:**

```java
import jakarta.persistence.*;

// Address is a value object — no ID, no lifecycle of its own:
@Embeddable
public class Address {
    @Column(name = "street", length = 200)
    private String street;

    @Column(name = "city", length = 100)
    private String city;

    @Column(name = "pincode", length = 10)
    private String pincode;

    @Column(name = "state", length = 50)
    private String state;

    // No @Id! Embeddable has no identity
    protected Address() {}
    public Address(String street, String city, String pincode, String state) {
        this.street=street; this.city=city; this.pincode=pincode; this.state=state;
    }
    // getters...
}

@Entity @Table(name = "orders")
public class Order {
    @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy=GenerationType.UUID) String id;

    @Embedded  // embedded: Address columns go INTO the orders table
    private Address shippingAddress;    // columns: street, city, pincode, state

    // Override column names when embedding twice:
    @Embedded
    @AttributeOverrides({
        @AttributeOverride(name="street",  column=@Column(name="billing_street")),
        @AttributeOverride(name="city",    column=@Column(name="billing_city")),
        @AttributeOverride(name="pincode", column=@Column(name="billing_pincode")),
        @AttributeOverride(name="state",   column=@Column(name="billing_state"))
    })
    private Address billingAddress;     // columns: billing_street, billing_city...
}
```

**Why @Embeddable instead of @Entity?**
```
@Entity Address: needs @Id, own table, own lifecycle, JPA creates proxy
@Embeddable Address: no ID, columns in parent table, no separate queries

Rule: if the concept has no independent identity (only exists as part of another entity)
      → @Embeddable
      If it exists independently (other entities reference it) → @Entity
```

concept_explanation.element_collection:
**@ElementCollection — collections of simple values or embeddables:**

```java
@Entity
public class Product {
    @Id String id;
    String name;

    // Collection of simple Strings (stored in a separate table):
    @ElementCollection
    @CollectionTable(
        name = "product_tags",
        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "product_id")
    )
    @Column(name = "tag")
    private Set<String> tags = new HashSet<>();
    // product_tags table: (product_id, tag)

    // Collection of embeddable (value object list):
    @ElementCollection
    @CollectionTable(
        name = "product_images",
        joinColumns = @JoinColumn(name = "product_id")
    )
    private List<ProductImage> images = new ArrayList<>();
    // product_images table: (product_id, url, alt_text, display_order)
}

@Embeddable
public class ProductImage {
    private String url;
    @Column(name = "alt_text") private String altText;
    @Column(name = "display_order") private int displayOrder;
    // no @Id
}

// Usage:
product.getTags().add("5G");
product.getTags().add("Smartphone");
product.getImages().add(new ProductImage("https://cdn.../img1.jpg", "Front view", 1));
productRepo.save(product);
// → INSERT INTO product_tags (product_id, tag) VALUES (?, '5G'), (?, 'Smartphone')
// → INSERT INTO product_images (product_id, url, ...) VALUES ...

// WARNING: Hibernate deletes all @ElementCollection rows then re-inserts on every save!
// Bad for large collections. Fine for small lists (< 20 items).
```

